<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Rainbows_End&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: External links">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">External links</span></h2>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?181278" class="external text" title="http://www.isfdb.org/cgi-bin/title.cgi?181278" rel="nofollow"><i>Rainbows End</i></a> publication history at the <a href="/wiki/Internet_Speculative_Fiction_Database" title="Internet Speculative Fiction Database" class="mw-redirect">Internet Speculative Fiction Database</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www-rohan.sdsu.edu/faculty/vinge/misc/singularity.html" class="external text" title="http://www-rohan.sdsu.edu/faculty/vinge/misc/singularity.html" rel="nofollow">The Coming Technological Singularity: How to Survive in the Post-Human Era, 1993</a> — An essay by Vinge about the possible causes and effects of technological singularity.</li>
<li><a href="http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/iel5/6/29070/01309803.pdf" class="external text" title="http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/iel5/6/29070/01309803.pdf" rel="nofollow">"Synthetic Serendipity"</a> — one of Vinge's two novellas set in the same world as <i>Rainbows End</i>, complete with illustrations (This novella is an extract from <i>Rainbows End</i>, although a few names and details have changed. You need to be a member of IEEE to read this extract).</li>
<li><a href="http://www.spectrum.ieee.org/jul04/3926" class="external text" title="http://www.spectrum.ieee.org/jul04/3926" rel="nofollow">Mike Villas's World</a> — IEEE article discussing the technology of the book.</li>
</ul>
